The UV–Vis absorption of CQDs, MnO2 NF and NS were studied to investigate their optical properties. The UV–Visible absorption spectra of CQDs displayed in Fig. 1(a) showed two absorption bands (λmax) at 245nm and 350nm plausible due to π→π* transition of the CC bond and n→π* transition of the CO respectively [31]. Similarly, two absorption bands at 214nm and 275nm were observed in the UV–Visible absorption spectra of MnO2 NF and NS. The CQDs showed maximum emission at 420nm when excited at 320nm (Fig. 1(b)). This scenario was monitored for different excitation wavelengths which is a usual characteristic of CQDs. Through their participation with MnO2 NF and NS leads to leads to effective quenching of the fluorescence emissions as shown in Fig. 2(d). The average hydrodynamic size has been found to be 7nm for CQDs (Fig. 2(a)), while the participation of MnO2 leads to agglomeration resulting in the increase of the size distribution up to 7.6nm (Fig. 2(b)–(c)). The zeta potential value for CQDs, MnO2 NF@CQDs and MnO2 NS@CQDs were observed to be −0.912mV, −2.24mV and −0.141mV respectively which confirm the negative charge on their surfaces. XPS measurements were performed to determine the composition of CQDs. As shown in Fig. 3
                        , the C 1s (285.31eV) and O 1s (532.97eV) peaks are the two major elements observed for CQDs. X-ray diffraction pattern of NF (Fig. 3(d)) show that the NF could be well indexed to tetragonal MnO2 as per the reference data (JCPDS 24-0735). The MnO2 NS were found to have greater surface area, pore volume and pore diameter than MnO2 NF (Fig. 4(a)) observed from the BET N2 adsoprtion-desorption curves for MnO2 NF and NS. These curves exhibited the Type-II classification which depict that these show large deviations from Langmuir model of adsorption and the intermediate flat region corresponds to monolayer formation [32]. The surface morphology and distribution of MnO2 nanostructures over CQDs have been determined by HRTEM, EDS analysis and color mapping. The EDS analysis (Fig. S1) clearly displays the successful formation of MnO2 nanostructures. The HRTEM image of MnO2 NF (Fig. 4(d)) displays the flower structures of MnO2, whereas Fig. 4(b) and Fig. 4(c) display MnO2 NS with lattice spacing of 0.40nm. Moreover, the attainment of the MnO2@CQDs composite is observed in elemental mapping (Fig. 5
                        ), which clearly shows that the CQDs are well combined on the surface of MnO2 nanostructures.

To promote the relevance and applicability of MnO2@CQDs as biosensor for pharmaceutical utility and in biological industries, the whole scheme was performed for several biomolecules and Enapril tablets. Enapril tablets contain Enalapril Maleate as an active ingredient and are generally used for treating high blood pressure and heart failure. The results recommended that the MnO2@CQDs composite is suitable for thiol containing biomolecules, as shown in Fig. 10
                        . The amino acids which do not contain free thiol groups aren't capable of exchanging the CQDs from MnO2 surface. The enhanced fluorescence intensity with the addition of 20μL enapril at each time is shown in Fig. 7(e) and Fig. 8(e). The turn-on fluorescence is linearly dependent upon the concentration of enapril with correlation coefficient of 0.9917 and observed LOD is 0.016μM (Fig. 7(f)) for MnO2 NF. Similarly, the turn-on fluorescence is linearly dependent upon the concentration of enapril with correlation coefficient of 0.9909 and observed LOD is 0.011μM (Fig. 8(f)) for MnO2 NS. Comparatively, this method is better than those previously reported techniques and biosensors (Table 1
                        ). This suggests that the composite is highly beneficial for the usage as a fluorescence sensor for bio-thiols.
